{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem *Husn o Ishq* (\"Beauty and Love\"), from *Bang-e-Dara Part 2*, he personifies **Beauty (Husn)** as a radiant, overwhelming force—likened to the sun eclipsing the moon, light cloaking a lotus, or Moses' divine hand at Sinai—that inspires and perfects **Love (Ishq)**, which the poet embodies as the responsive heart.[^1] Love reaches its \"culmination\" through Beauty's \"lightning-flash,\" finding direction, repose, and manifestation only in its presence: \"From Beauty, Love's own nature is spurred toward perfection.\"[^2] Thus, Beauty is the divine spark and catalyst driving Love to fulfillment, while Love animates and completes Beauty's essence.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, \"Husn o Ishq\" [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/13-husn-o-ishq/translation/#p-3bf497).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, \"Husn o Ishq\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/13-husn-o-ishq/translation/#p-7a49e3).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, \"Husn o Ishq\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/13-husn-o-ishq/translation/#p-73eab8).",
